{"dataset":"articles","provider":"pursuit","banner_url":"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/73064/Too-many-Aussies-are-starting-a-family-and-raising-their-kids-in-poverty_49fcb38d-67af-4300-b8ed-fff0aab52112.jpg","id":"73057","text":"<div class=\"container\"><span><p>Australia is a high-income country with universal health, education and social services. But, like many countries around the world, Australia is in the midst of a <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/more-than-half-of-australians-are-only-just-making-ends-meet\" target=\"_self\">cost-of-living crisis</a>.</p><p>In fact, at least <a href=\"https://melbourneinstitute.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0008/4841909/HILDA_Statistical_Report_2023.pdf\" target=\"_self\">one in three families with children experience deprivation</a>, missing out on essential items like food, stable housing and healthcare. And this is something that’s more pronounced for families with <a href=\"https://melbourneinstitute.unimelb.edu.au/publications/research-insights/search/result?paper=3934439\" target=\"_self\">children under five years</a> of age.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/73064/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/73064/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/73064/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/73064/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/73064/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/73064/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/73064/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/73064/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/73064/Too-many-Aussies-are-starting-a-family-and-raising-their-kids-in-poverty_49fcb38d-67af-4300-b8ed-fff0aab52112.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>The arrival of the first child reduces household income between 16-18 per cent. Picture: Getty Images</figcaption></figure></div><span><p>Even by the time Australian children start school, developmental inequities are evident stemming from adverse social conditions – like poverty.</p><p>Children living in Australian suburbs experiencing the most disadvantage have <a href=\"https://www.aedc.gov.au/\" target=\"_self\">three times the developmental vulnerability</a> of those living in the most advantaged (19 per cent versus seven per cent).</p><p>Our <a href=\"https://melbourneinstitute.unimelb.edu.au/publications/working-papers/search/result?paper=4812466\" target=\"_self\">research</a> – the result of a partnership between the <a href=\"https://melbourneinstitute.unimelb.edu.au/\" target=\"_self\">Melbourne Institute: Applied Economic & Social Research</a> and the <a href=\"https://www.mcri.edu.au/research/research-areas/population-health/centre-for-community-child-health\" target=\"_self\">Centre for Community Child Health</a> at the <a href=\"https://www.mcri.edu.au/\" target=\"_self\">Murdoch Children’s Research Institute</a> – has found that the arrival of the first child reduces household income and increases the probability of poverty.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0027/73755/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Business &amp; Economics</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/more-than-half-of-australians-are-only-just-making-ends-meet?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>More than half of Australians are only just making ends meet <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><h2 class=\"center\">The cost of a first child</h2></span><span><p>The arrival of the first child reduces household income between 16-18 per cent on average.</p><p>This drop is higher for one-parent households (23-27 per cent) than for two-parent households.</p><p>Five years after the birth of a first child, household income has not returned to its original level, stabilising at around 18.3 per cent below the pre-childbirth income.</p><p>The reduction in a woman’s hours of work, employment and hourly wages, following the arrival of children, explain much of this drop.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0016/73060/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0016/73060/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0016/73060/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0016/73060/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0016/73060/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0016/73060/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0016/73060/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0016/73060/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0016/73060/Too-many-Aussies-are-starting-a-family-and-raising-their-kids-in-poverty_3d7ee7c1-c89b-48d1-823e-f784fd23f324.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>This graph shows the impact of first childbirth on household disposable income. The vertical line refers to the year before the arrival of the first child. The shaded areas are the 95 per cent confidence intervals. Graphic: Supplied. </figcaption></figure></div><span><p><a href=\"https://treasury.gov.au/publication/p2023-372004\" target=\"_self\">Australia’s motherhood penalty</a> – the severe wage and hiring disadvantages that mothers face in the workplace – is one of the highest among high-income countries. This is due in part to the relatively <a href=\"https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=4520289\" target=\"_self\">conservative norms</a> experienced by Australian men and women compared to other countries.</p><p>Other factors – like job loss, separation and more children – may contribute to the lack of recovery, even five years after the birth of a first child<span class=\"bold\">.</span></p></span><span><h2 class=\"center\">The difference between one and two-parent households</h2></span><span><p>The change in household income at childbirth relates to poverty.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0015/78000/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Health &amp; Medicine</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/women-are-doing-too-much-and-it-s-hurting-their-mental-health?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>Women are doing too much and it’s hurting their mental health <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>We found 37 to 40 per cent of households stayed or moved into or near poverty in each of the five years following the arrival of their first newborn.</p><p>Movement between poverty categories was substantially greater for one-parent than two-parent households.</p><p>For one-parent households, 23-32 per cent remained out of poverty, four to six per cent moved out of poverty or near poverty, and 63-70 per cent stayed in or moved into poverty or near poverty.</p><p>If we look at two-parent households, 61-64 per cent remained out of poverty, two to four per cent moved out of poverty or near poverty, and 34-36 per cent stayed in or moved into poverty or near poverty.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/73065/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/73065/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/73065/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/73065/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/73065/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/73065/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/73065/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/73065/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/73065/Too-many-Aussies-are-starting-a-family-and-raising-their-kids-in-poverty_5f7928ae-5c9c-41df-b9e8-f619c77854f3.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>For one-parent households, the absence of partner earnings contributes to a higher poverty risk. Picture: Getty Images</figcaption></figure></div><span><p>We also found the probability of poverty for new parents is, on average, 12 per cent for all households, 17 per cent for one-parent households and 10 per cent for two-parent households</p><p>For one-parent households, the <a href=\"https://read.dukeupress.edu/demography/article/59/4/1377/315802/The-Accumulation-of-Economic-Disadvantage-The\" target=\"_self\">absence of partner earnings</a> contributes to a higher poverty risk than for two-parent households.</p></span><span><h2 class=\"center\">Government protection from poverty</h2></span><span><p>So, do the Australian government’s family payments help mitigate poverty around the birth of a first child?</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/85133/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Business &amp; Economics</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/child-care-a-challenge-for-poorer-single-parents?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>Child care a challenge for poorer single parents <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>The short answer is yes. Without family payments, the average poverty rate increases from 26 per cent for one-parent households and 10 per cent for two-parent households before childbirth, to 63 per cent and 20 per cent, respectively, in the following years.</p><p>With family payments, the average poverty rates after childbirth are 37 per cent and 11 per cent, respectively.</p><p>While family payments do help reduce poverty among households with a first baby, these payments do not protect them from falling into poverty.</p><p>Even with family payments, a substantial number of Australia families are starting a family and raising their children in poverty.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/73059/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/73059/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/73059/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/73059/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/73059/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/73059/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/73059/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/73059/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/73059/Too-many-Aussies-are-starting-a-family-and-raising-their-kids-in-poverty_d68d36c0-7847-489c-8e97-cb08a2bc531d.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>This graph shows poverty rates during childbirth. The family benefits considered are Parenting Payments, Family Tax Benefits (Part A and B), Maternity Allowance, and the Single Income Family Bonus (SIFS). The shaded areas are the 95 per cent confidence intervals. Graphic: Supplied. </figcaption></figure></div><span><h2 class=\"center\">A buffer against poverty</h2></span><span><p>In Australia, there is increasing interest in equitable policy and support for low-income families. This can be seen in the <a href=\"https://treasury.gov.au/publication/p2023-mwm\" target=\"_self\">national wellbeing budget</a> and increases to <a href=\"https://www.abc.net.au/news/2023-07-10/childcare-subsidies-are-increasing-here-s-what-you-need-to-know/102581828\" target=\"_self\">childcare subsidies</a> and <a href=\"https://www.fairwork.gov.au/newsroom/news/awr-2023\" target=\"_self\">minimum wage</a>.</p><p>The importance of early childhood and support for parents is also gaining prominence through the <a href=\"https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/national-action-plan-for-the-health-of-children-and-young-people-2020-2030\" target=\"_self\">National Action Plan for the Health of Children and Young People 2020-2030</a>, the proposed <a href=\"https://archive.budget.gov.au/2022-23-october/bp2/download/bp2_2022-23.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Early Years Strategy</a> and the <a href=\"https://www.education.gov.au/early-childhood/announcements/federal-budget-commits-45-billion-more-affordable-child-care\" target=\"_self\">Plan for Affordable Child Care</a>.</p><p>But how well are these policies buffering families from the risk of poverty? And given Australia’s <a href=\"https://www.aph.gov.au/About_Parliament/Parliamentary_departments/Parliamentary_Library/pubs/BriefingBook47p/RisingInflationAndMacroeconomicBalance\" target=\"_self\">increasing inflation</a> and <a href=\"https://www.aph.gov.au/About_Parliament/Parliamentary_departments/Parliamentary_Library/pubs/BriefingBook47p/CostOfLiving\" target=\"_self\">cost of living</a>, is there a case for investing more heavily during the early childhood?</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/73066/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/73066/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/73066/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/73066/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/73066/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/73066/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/73066/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/73066/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/73066/Too-many-Aussies-are-starting-a-family-and-raising-their-kids-in-poverty_23c0605f-d0ad-41b1-9c9c-ab750588aa93.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Five years after the birth of a first child, household income has not returned to its original level. Picture: Getty Images</figcaption></figure></div><span><p>Although poverty is defined by household income, actions to halve or even eradicate child poverty are more complex than increasing household income alone.</p><p>Addressing child poverty requires a more <a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29263179/\" target=\"_self\">comprehensive approach</a>, a rigorous understanding of the extent of the problem and identification of points for change.</p><p>Our analysis is a necessary step in understanding why so many Australian families are raising their young children in poverty – and the steps we can take as a nation to prevent it.</p><p>Banner: Getty Images</p></span></div>\n<p>This article was first published on <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\">Pursuit</a>. <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/too-many-aussies-are-starting-a-family-and-raising-their-kids-in-poverty\">Read the original article.</a></p>","date_published":"2024-02-21T14:51:39+11:00","date_updated":"2024-02-21T14:51:39+11:00","url":"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/too-many-aussies-are-starting-a-family-and-raising-their-kids-in-poverty","title":"Too many Aussies are starting a family and raising their kids in poverty","summary":"New research finds that the birth of a first child reduces household income and increases the risk of disadvantage","org_objects":[],"tag_objects":[],"author_objects":[{"name":"Dr Ana Gamarra Rondinel","url":"https:\\/\\/pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\\/individuals\\/dr-ana-gamarra-rondinel","orcid":"","fae_url":"https://findanexpert.unimelb.edu.au/profile/870323-ana-gamarra-rondinel","email":""},{"name":"Dr Anna MH Price","url":"https:\\/\\/pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\\/individuals\\/dr-anna-mh-price","orcid":"","fae_url":"https://findanexpert.unimelb.edu.au/profile/98458-anna-price","email":""}],"citation_objects":[{"credentials":"Dr Ana Gamarra Rondinel"},{"credentials":"Dr Anna MH Price"}]}